## Service 3 — Notification Service (Port 8083)

### What it does
This service **logs and manages notifications**. Whenever something important happens in the system — like stock going low, an item being deleted, or an order being placed — a notification is recorded. It stores who was notified, what happened, and when.

### Database Table

```
notifications table in MySQL (notification_db)
┌────┬───────────┬──────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────┐
│ id │ event_type│ recipient                │ message                          │ sent_at             │
├────┼───────────┼──────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤
│  1 │ LowStock  │ manager@company.com      │ Stock for item 1005 dropped low  │ 2025-07-28 11:00:00 │
│  2 │ ItemAdded │ admin@company.com        │ New item Wireless Mouse added    │ 2025-07-28 09:00:00 │
└────┴───────────┴──────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────┘
```

### APIs Available

```
POST   /api/notifications              → Send/log a new notification
GET    /api/notifications              → Get all notification logs
GET    /api/notifications/1            → Get notification by id
GET    /api/notifications/event/LowStock → Get all LowStock notifications
PUT    /api/notifications/1            → Update notification
DELETE /api/notifications/1            → Delete notification entry
```

### What you send to create a notification (JSON)

```json
{
  "eventType": "LowStock",
  "recipient": "inventory.manager@company.com",
  "message": "Stock for item 1005 has dropped below threshold."
}
```

### What you get back

```json
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Notification sent successfully",
  "data": {
    "id": 1,
    "eventType": "LowStock",
    "recipient": "inventory.manager@company.com",
    "message": "Stock for item 1005 has dropped below threshold.",
    "sentAt": "2025-07-28T11:00:00"
  }
}
```

