## What is ApiResponse

Every single API response in this project looks the same — whether success or failure. This consistency is called a **standard response format**.

```java
Success looks like:
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Item created successfully",
  "data": { actual item data here }
}

Failure looks like:
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "Item not found with id: 99",
  "data": null
}
```

This makes it easy for any frontend application to always know what to expect from our APIs.

---

## What is GlobalExceptionHandler

Without this, if something goes wrong Java would return a horrible 50-line error message. With GlobalExceptionHandler, every error gets caught and converted to a clean JSON response.

```
Item not found  →  404 with clean message
Validation fail →  400 with field-by-field errors
Any other error →  500 with safe generic message
                   (no sensitive details exposed)
```

---

## What is JWT Security

JWT is a **token-based security system**. Every API request must carry a token to prove the caller is authorized.

```
Without token:
YOU → request → JwtAuthFilter → BLOCKED → 401 Unauthorized

With valid token:
YOU → request + token → JwtAuthFilter → validates → ALLOWED → Controller runs

With expired/wrong token:
YOU → request + bad token → JwtAuthFilter → BLOCKED → 401 Unauthorized
```

The token is generated using a **secret key** that only our server knows. Nobody can fake a token without knowing the secret key.

